handoffs (they are supposed to ephereral, consumed upon use). What other housekeeping things can you think of?\n\nAnd should it live in CMS or brain2?'), (203,2,'2026-06-17 11:36:18','3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48ee6174','edit_path','tools/cms_manifest.py',NULL,'fc48c240cda9f661a5910ceaa833ce91acbea2fb',1,'claude-sonnet-4-6','0.1.0','# Payload → project file mapping for cms_lint.py and cms_update.py.\n# Verbatim-copied artifacts only. Excludes:\n#   - *.md.template files (filled at instantiation, then project-modified)\n#   - tools/lint.py (comes from lint_skeleton.py but gets project-specific checks added)\n#   - mine-session skill (installed by Monition, not CMS directly)\n\nMANIFEST = [\n    # (payload_relative_path, project_relative_path)\n    (\"payload/skills/codify/SKILL.md\",           \".claude/skills/codify/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/dispatch/SKILL.md\",         \".claude/skills/dispatch/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/handoff/SKILL.md\",          \".claude/skills/handoff/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/wrap-session/SKILL.md\",     \".claude/skills/wrap-session/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/catch-me-up/SKILL.md\",      \".claude/skills/catch-me-up/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/confer/SKILL.md\",           \".claude/skills/confer/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/diagnose-process/SKILL.md\", \".claude/skills/diagnose-process/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/skills/grill-me/SKILL.md\",         \".claude/skills/grill-me/SKILL.md\"),\n    (\"payload/.githooks/pre-commit\",             \".githooks/pre-commit\"),\n    (\"payload/hooks/craft_reminder.py\",          \"tools/craft_reminder.py\"),\n    (\"payload/hooks/session_tokens.py\",          \"tools/session_tokens.py\"),\n    (\"payload/tools/lessons_fire.py\",            \"tools/lessons_fire.py\"),\n    (\"payload/tools/extract_session.py\",         \"tools/extract_session.py\"),\n]\n\n\ndef cms_projects(projects_dir, cms_root):\n    \"\"\"Yield (name, path) for CMS-instantiated projects (have .githooks/pre-commit).\"\"\"\n    import os\n    for name in sorted(os.listdir(projects_dir)):\n        d = os.path.join(projects_dir, name)\n        if d == cms_root or not os.path.isdir(d):\n            continue\n        if os.path.exists(os.path.join(d, \".githooks\", \"pre-commit\")):\n            yield name, d\n'), (204,3,'2026-06-17 13:34:33','fc012ea6-da25-49e5-942b-086220f1bc93','session_start',NULL,NULL,'fc48c240cda9f661a5910ceaa833ce91acbea2fb',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0',NULL), (205,9,'2026-06-17 15:26:27','3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48ee6174','edit_path','method/takeaway-store.md','noise','020db36ad71f06fbe005b30ac269de5c8fc42b13',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','## Wiring (downstream)\n\nA store is created with `monition init` (Monition is a declared prerequisite). The\nblock format is defined in Monition\'s store contract (cite, never duplicate).'), (206,20,'2026-06-17 15:27:07','3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48ee6174','on_demand','<task-notification>\n<task-id>aaf44342b0ebcbcfc</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01RT7Mjk4VBF1jiXRHruHyDQ</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-bolun-projects-CMS/3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48',NULL,'020db36ad71f06fbe005b30ac269de5c8fc42b13',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','<task-notification>\n<task-id>aaf44342b0ebcbcfc</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01RT7Mjk4VBF1jiXRHruHyDQ</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-bolun-projects-CMS/3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48ee6174/tasks/aaf44342b0ebcbcfc.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"CMS removals: generator + tier-0 + drift tooling\" completed</summary>\n<result>Clean. Here are the verbatim outputs as requested:\n\n**`python3 ~/projects/CMS/tools/cms_lint.py`:**\n```\nexit code: 0\n```\n(no output — 0 errors, 0 warnings)\n\n**`git -C ~/projects/CMS status`:**\n```\nOn branch refactor-forkable\nChanges not staged for commit:\n  (use \"git add/rm &lt;file&gt;...\" to update what will be committed)\n  (use \"git restore &lt;file&gt;...\" to discard changes in working directory)\n\tdeleted:    .claude/skills/instantiate/SKILL.md\n\tdeleted:    method/instantiate.md\n\tmodified:   method/takeaway-store.md\n\tdeleted:    payload/lessons.md.template\n\tdeleted:    payload/tools/lessons_fire.py\n\tmodified:   tools/cms_lint.py\n\tdeleted:    tools/cms_manifest.py\n\tdeleted:    tools/cms_update.py\n\nno changes added to commit (use \"git add\" and/or \"git commit -a\")\n```\n\nAll 8 changes are unstaged in the working tree. No commit was made.\n\n---\n\nSummary of what was done:\n\n- **Deleted** `.claude/skills/instantiate/SKILL.md` and `method/instantiate.md` (generator killed)\n- **Deleted** `payload/tools/lessons_fire.py` and `payload/lessons.md.template` (tier-0 killed)\n- **Deleted** `tools/cms_manifest.py` and `tools/cms_update.py` (drift tooling killed)\n- **Edited** `tools/cms_lint.py`: removed `check_payload_drift`, its `GLOBAL_CHECKS` entry, the `from cms_manifest import ...` import, the `sys.path.insert(...)` line, and the now-unused `PROJECTS_DIR` constant. `check_upstream_candidates` and all other checks are intact.\n- **Edited** `method/takeaway-store.md` §\"Wiring (downstream)\": replaced the tier-0 framing (frozen executor, `lessons.md`, `monition init --adopt` graduation) with a single-sentence statement that `monition init` creates the store. §\"Dolt mechanics\" is untouched.\n- **Consistency check**: no markdown hyperlinks in `method/` or `docs/` pointed to any deleted file — all references were prose-only, which the linter does not check, and the plan reserves those rewrites for a separate workstream.\n\n## Takeaways\n\n**Decisions made:**\n- `PROJECTS_DIR` was removed from `cms_lint.py` as a byproduct — it was only used by `check_payload_drift`. Removing it keeps the file honest rather than leaving a dead constant.\n- Prose references to `instantiate`, `lessons_fire.py`, and `lessons.md` in `docs/DESIGN.md` were left intentionally — they\'re not broken links (no `[text](target)` form), and the plan explicitly defers that prose rewrite to Workstream A.\n\n**Gotchas hit:**\n- The baseline linter produced 8 WARNs (all payload-drift). After removing `check_payload_drift`, those WARNs vanish — the linter is now cleaner than baseline, not just equal. Worth flagging so the parent session knows the WARN count drop is expected.\n- `method/takeaway-store.md` fired takeaway t9/f205 on edit: \"Creating or extending a method discipline another repo must mirror? Assign the canonical owner and the propagation channel in the same change.\" The edit was a deletion/simplification, not an extension, so the takeaway is noise here — but the discipline is sound for Workstream C when skills move to single-source.\n\n**Lessons worth keeping:**\n- When removing a function that owns a module-level import (`from cms_manifest import ...`) and a module-level constant (`PROJECTS_DIR`), sweep for both in the same pass — the import removal is obvious but the constant becomes silently dead.\n- The linter\'s `check_relative_links` skips `payload/` paths entirely (they resolve in the generated project). This means broken links inside payload templates never surface — a known gap to keep in mind when Workstream C moves payload content into `tools/` or `starter/`.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>32794</subagent_tok'), (207,18,'2026-06-17 15:34:17','3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48ee6174','on_demand','<task-notification>\n<task-id>a41258b6d2329bdd9</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01KsRvbqKkabDHPzY49gbp1A</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-bolun-projects-CMS/3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48',NULL,'0804a826ecd5434c5b8c7d40705c4a6b0460c528',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','<task-notification>\n<task-id>a41258b6d2329bdd9</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01KsRvbqKkabDHPzY49gbp1A</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-bolun-projects-CMS/3c7864d6-7af8-4891-a1b3-d46f48ee6174/tasks/a41258b6d2329bdd9.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"CMS structural moves: starter/ + tools/\" completed</summary>\n<result>All 8 renames staged, linter fix staged, linter exits 0. Here is the verbatim output of both verification commands:\n\n**`python3 ~/projects/CMS/tools/cms_lint.py`** — no output, exit code: 0\n\n**`git -C ~/projects/CMS status`:**\n```\nOn branch refactor-forkable\nChanges to be committed:\n  (use \"git restore --staged &lt;file&gt;...\" to unstage)\n\trenamed:    payload/CLAUDE.md.template -&gt; starter/CLAUDE.md.template\n\trenamed:    payload/debt.md.template -&gt; starter/debt.md.template\n\trenamed:    payload/prompts/workstream_bucket_generator.md -&gt; starter/prompts/workstream_bucket_generator.md\n\trenamed:    payload/road.md.template -&gt; starter/road.md.template\n\tmodified:   tools/cms_lint.py\n\trenamed:    payload/hooks/craft_reminder.py -&gt; tools/craft_reminder.py\n\trenamed:    payload/tools/extract_session.py -&gt; tools/extract_session.py\n\trenamed:    payload/tools/lint_skeleton.py -&gt; tools/lint_skeleton.py\n\trenamed:    payload/hooks/session_tokens.py -&gt; tools/session_tokens.py\n```\n\n**What was done:**\n- 4 per-project identity templates moved `payload/` → `starter/` (with `starter/prompts/` created)\n- 4 shared machinery files moved: 2 from `payload/hooks/` and 2 from `payload/tools/` → `tools/`\n- `payload/skills/` and `payload/.githooks/` untouched\n- `payload/hooks/` and `payload/prompts/` now contain only `__pycache__` (untracked); git will drop the dirs in the commit naturally\n- `payload/tools/` same situation — `__pycache__` only, no tracked files remain\n- `tools/cms_lint.py` updated: `check_unfilled_placeholders` now exempts `starter/` alongside `payload/` — the only linter change needed\n- No markdown `[text](path)` links to moved files found in `method/`, `docs/`, or `README.md` — all references were prose backtick mentions, no repairs needed\n\n## Takeaways\n\n**Decision:** `check_unfilled_placeholders` in the linter must be updated whenever a new directory is designated as a template home. The exemption list (`payload/` → `payload/ or starter/`) is the single-source enforcement of \"placeholders live only in template dirs\" — it must track the directory topology. This was a required mechanical fix, not a behavior change to the governance rule.\n\n**Gotcha:** The linter\'s placeholder check uses `rel.startswith(\"payload\")` as a string prefix check, not a path component check. A dir named e.g. `payload_old/` would also be exempted. For `starter/` the same prefix logic works fine, but a future rename should verify this doesn\'t accidentally exempt unintended paths.\n\n**Gotcha:** All prose references to moved files in `method/` and `docs/` use backtick inline code, not `[text](path)` markdown links — so `check_relative_links` had nothing to repair. This is the correct authoring style for file path references in this codebase (prose mentions, not links), and the linter\'s link check correctly ignores them.\n\n**Lesson:** Before any structural file move in CMS, run `grep -rn \'\\[.*\\](.*&lt;target-path&gt;)\'` against `method/`, `docs/`, and `README.md` to isolate actual markdown links from prose mentions. Prose mentions are invisible to the linter and don\'t need updating.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>24387</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>20</tool_uses><duration_ms>91984</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>'), (208,3,'2026-06-18 03:21:30','6d82d5ae-b836-40db-8047-596f8a30156b','session_start',NULL,'helpful','761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',0,'claude-sonnet-4-6','0.1.0',NULL), (209,7,'2026-06-18 04:01:55','6d82d5ae-b836-40db-8047-596f8a30156b','on_demand','Can I spawn an agent to resume a session based on a stub and then run /mine-session in there?','noise','761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',0,'claude-sonnet-4-6','0.1.0','Can I spawn an agent to resume a session based on a stub and then run /mine-session in there?'), (210,3,'2026-06-18 10:22:40','b5f6b8f0-e94b-45c5-92b5-f7a56c7607fc','session_start',NULL,NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0',NULL), (211,3,'2026-06-18 11:33:18','6b9182e6-75bd-4fca-b800-285bb33d00d6','session_start',NULL,NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0',NULL), (212,3,'2026-06-18 11:43:59','b5d35316-20a4-4481-bf6c-f1e0a5ee87b7','session_start',NULL,NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0',NULL), (213,2,'2026-06-18 13:41:33','6d82d5ae-b836-40db-8047-596f8a30156b','edit_path','tools/session_tokens.py','noise','761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-sonnet-4-6','0.1.0','DEFAULT_LOG_PATH = Path.home() / \'.claude\' / \'logs\' / \'sessions.md\'\nDIAGNOSTIC_LOG_PATH = Path.home() / \'.claude\' / \'logs\' / \'session-tokens.log\'\n\n# Sessions whose cwd contains any of these fragments are skipped — they are\n# subagent spawns, worktrees, or temp dirs that don\'t produce session-level\n# knowledge worth indexing. Override by setting CMS_SKIP_CWD (colon-separated).\n_DEFAULT_SKIP_CWD_FRAGMENTS = (\n  \'/tmp/\', \'/-tmp-\', \'/cache/agent-spawn\', \'/cache/agent-workstream\',\n  \'superset-worktrees\', \'agent-spawn-worktrees\',\n)\nSKIP_CWD_FRAGMENTS: tuple[str, ...] = tuple(\n  f for f in os.environ.get(\'CMS_SKIP_CWD\', \'\').split(\':\') if f\n) or _DEFAULT_SKIP_CWD_FRAGMENTS\n\n# Sessions with fewer real user turns than this are drive-bys and skipped.\nMIN_USER_TURNS = 2\n\n# Counter fields summed into the log, plus the non-counter fields'), (214,2,'2026-06-18 13:42:56','6b9182e6-75bd-4fca-b800-285bb33d00d6','edit_path','tools/autoflag.py',NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\"\"\"Stop hook: deterministic backstop for the two-tier autoflagger.\n\nTier 1 is the agent itself — a CLAUDE.md rule has it self-flag flag-worthy moments\ninline (the semantic judgment, free, with full context). This script is tier 2: a\nmechanical net that catches one unambiguous, keyword-detectable class the agent might\nskip — an *admitted error* in the just-finished response (the same pattern\n`mine-session` step 0b hunts). It appends a GOVERNANCE flag to the same\n`~/.claude/session-flags.md` that `/flag` writes and `/mine-session` drains.\n\nNo LLM call: regex only. Three load-bearing properties, mirroring craft_reminder.py —\nfires at most once per matched snippet (a backstop that repeats becomes noise), never\nblocks the stop, and fails open (malformed input or any error exits silently; a\nbookmark has no business stopping work).\n\nWire in .claude/settings.json:\n\n    {\"hooks\": {\"Stop\": [{\"hooks\": [\n        {\"type\": \"command\", \"command\": \"python3 tools/autoflag.py\"}]}]}}\n\n(Path is relative to the project; use \"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/autoflag.py\" if the\nhook may run from another cwd.)\n\"\"\"\nimport hashlib\nimport json\nimport os\nimport re\nimport sys\nfrom datetime import date\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nFLAGS_FILE = Path.home() / \".claude\" / \"session-flags.md\"\n\n# Admitted-error patterns — kept tight to avoid false positives. Each marks a moment\n# mine-session step 0b would treat as a governance-change candidate.\nPATTERNS = [\n    r\"\\bI was wrong\\b\",\n    r\"\\bI was mistaken\\b\",\n    r\"\\bmy mistake\\b\",\n    r\"\\bI should have (?:checked|verified|read|tested|looked|run)\\b\",\n    r\"\\bI (?:asserted|claimed|said|stated|assumed)\\b[^.]{0,60}\\bwithout (?:verifying|checking|testing|reading)\\b\",\n    r\"\\bI didn\'?t (?:verify|check|test|read|run)\\b\",\n    r\"\\bI (?:incorrectly|wrongly|falsely) (?:assumed|claimed|stated|said|reported)\\b\",\n    r\"\\bturns out (?:I was|that was) (?:wrong|mistaken|incorrect)\\b\",\n]\n_RX = re.compile(\"|\".join(PATTERNS), re.IGNORECASE)\n\n\ndef last_assistant_text(transcript_path):\n    \"\"\"Return the text of the final assistant message in the transcript, or \'\'.\"\"\"\n    text = \"\"\n    try:\n        with open(transcript_path, encoding=\"utf-8\") as fh:\n            for line in fh:\n                line = line.strip()\n                if not line:\n                    continue\n                try:\n                    obj = json.loads(line)\n                except Exception:\n                    continue\n                if obj.get(\"type\") != \"assistant\":\n                    continue\n                content = (obj.get(\"message\") or {}).get(\"content\")\n                if isinstance(content, str):\n                    text = content\n                elif isinstance(content, list):\n                    parts = [\n                        b.get(\"text\", \"\")\n                        for b in content\n                        if isinstance(b, dict) and b.get(\"type\") == \"text\"\n                    ]\n                    if any(parts):\n                        text = \"\\n\".join(p for p in parts if p)\n    except Exception:\n        return \"\"\n    return text\n\n\ndef matched_sentence(text, match):\n    \"\"\"The sentence containing the match, trimmed to a one-liner.\"\"\"\n    start = text.rfind(\".\", 0, match.start()) + 1\n    end = text.find(\".\", match.end())\n    end = len(text) if end == -1 else end + 1\n    sentence = \" \".join(text[start:end].split())\n    return sentence[:160].rstrip()\n\n\ndef main():\n    try:\n        data = json.load(sys.stdin)\n    except Exception:\n        return  # fail open\n\n    # Don\'t act on a stop the agent is already being forced to continue.\n    if data.get(\"stop_hook_active\"):\n        return\n\n    transcript = data.get(\"transcript_path\")\n    if not transcript:\n        return\n\n    text = last_assistant_text(transcript)\n    if not text:\n        return\n\n    m = _RX.search(text)\n    if not m:\n        return\n\n    summary = matched_sentence(text, m)\n\n    # Dedup: one flag per (session, matched-snippet). craft_reminder.py uses the same\n    # /tmp-mark'), (215,5,'2026-06-18 13:43:28','6b9182e6-75bd-4fca-b800-285bb33d00d6','edit_path','.claude/settings.json',NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','    \"Stop\": [\n      {\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"python3 \\\"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/autoflag.py\\\"\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ],\n    \"SessionEnd\": [\n      {\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"python3 \\\"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/session_tokens.py\\\"\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ],'), (216,6,'2026-06-18 13:43:30','6b9182e6-75bd-4fca-b800-285bb33d00d6','edit_path','.claude/settings.json',NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','    \"Stop\": [\n      {\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"python3 \\\"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/autoflag.py\\\"\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ],\n    \"SessionEnd\": [\n      {\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"python3 \\\"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/session_tokens.py\\\"\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ],'), (217,5,'2026-06-18 14:04:49','6d82d5ae-b836-40db-8047-596f8a30156b','edit_path','.claude/skills/wrap-session/SKILL.md','helpful','761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-sonnet-4-6','0.1.0','---\nname: wrap-session\ndescription: Wrap a session into the global session archive — a rich, embedding-friendly summary file plus a one-line index entry — so a half-remembered future query (\"I remember working on X\") can be found by progressive disclosure. Live mode (no argument): summarizes from the current context window. Backfill mode (/wrap-session <session-id>): reads the transcript to wrap a missed past session. Use when the user invokes /wrap-session [session-id], says \"wrap this session\" / \"archive this session\" / \"backfill session <id>\", or is ending a session worth being able to find again. NOT for a decision-ready resume of in-flight work (that\'s /handoff).\n---\n\n# wrap-session\n\nTwo modes depending on whether an argument was passed:\n\n**Live mode** (no argument): you are wrapping the current session. Governing\nprinciple: **summarize only from what is already in your context window.** The\nprompt cache is warm; re-reading the transcript spends tokens to re-derive what\nyou already hold.\n\n**Backfill mode** (`/wrap-session <session-id-or-path>`): the live window was\nmissed; wrap from the transcript instead. Quality will be lower than a live wrap\n(compacted content is unrecoverable; only text turns survive extraction). Use for\nimportant missed sessions, not every drive-by.\n\nTwo writes — the rich summary file (rung 2 of the disclosure ladder) and the\none-line index entry in `sessions.md` (rung 1). **Fail open:** if a step\'s input\nis missing, write what you can. An index line with no token counts still beats no\ntrace.\n\n1. **Identify the session and establish the content source.**\n\n   *Live mode:* Get the session marker and provisional token line from the\n   session-token helper in `--print` mode. Find it at\n   `$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/session_tokens.py` and run `python3 <path> --print`.\n   It prints a `<!-- session: <id> -->` marker and a `tokens:` line. This\n   session\'s id is `$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` (the harness sets it per session) —\n   the source of truth, because newest-by-mtime misidentifies the session when\n   another runs in the same cwd concurrently. If neither helper path exists, take\n   the marker id from `$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` (fall back to the newest\n   `~/.claude/projects/<cwd-slug>/<id>.jsonl`) and skip the counts. Content source\n   is the context window — do not re-read the transcript.\n\n   *Backfill mode:* The argument is either a session ID or a `.jsonl` path.\n   - If it looks like a path: use it directly; session ID is the filename stem.\n   - If it looks like an ID: `find ~/.claude/projects -name \"<id>.jsonl\" 2>/dev/null | head -1`\n     to locate the transcript.\n   - Run `python3 $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/extract_session.py <jsonl-path> --cap 40000`\n     and read its output — this is your content source instead of the context window.\n   - There is no live `tokens:` line to write; the SessionEnd hook already wrote\n     one in the floor entry. Preserve it when updating the index entry in step 3.'), (218,6,'2026-06-18 14:04:54','6d82d5ae-b836-40db-8047-596f8a30156b','edit_path','.claude/skills/wrap-session/SKILL.md','noise','761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-sonnet-4-6','0.1.0','---\nname: wrap-session\ndescription: Wrap a session into the global session archive — a rich, embedding-friendly summary file plus a one-line index entry — so a half-remembered future query (\"I remember working on X\") can be found by progressive disclosure. Live mode (no argument): summarizes from the current context window. Backfill mode (/wrap-session <session-id>): reads the transcript to wrap a missed past session. Use when the user invokes /wrap-session [session-id], says \"wrap this session\" / \"archive this session\" / \"backfill session <id>\", or is ending a session worth being able to find again. NOT for a decision-ready resume of in-flight work (that\'s /handoff).\n---\n\n# wrap-session\n\nTwo modes depending on whether an argument was passed:\n\n**Live mode** (no argument): you are wrapping the current session. Governing\nprinciple: **summarize only from what is already in your context window.** The\nprompt cache is warm; re-reading the transcript spends tokens to re-derive what\nyou already hold.\n\n**Backfill mode** (`/wrap-session <session-id-or-path>`): the live window was\nmissed; wrap from the transcript instead. Quality will be lower than a live wrap\n(compacted content is unrecoverable; only text turns survive extraction). Use for\nimportant missed sessions, not every drive-by.\n\nTwo writes — the rich summary file (rung 2 of the disclosure ladder) and the\none-line index entry in `sessions.md` (rung 1). **Fail open:** if a step\'s input\nis missing, write what you can. An index line with no token counts still beats no\ntrace.\n\n1. **Identify the session and establish the content source.**\n\n   *Live mode:* Get the session marker and provisional token line from the\n   session-token helper in `--print` mode. Find it at\n   `$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/session_tokens.py` and run `python3 <path> --print`.\n   It prints a `<!-- session: <id> -->` marker and a `tokens:` line. This\n   session\'s id is `$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` (the harness sets it per session) —\n   the source of truth, because newest-by-mtime misidentifies the session when\n   another runs in the same cwd concurrently. If neither helper path exists, take\n   the marker id from `$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` (fall back to the newest\n   `~/.claude/projects/<cwd-slug>/<id>.jsonl`) and skip the counts. Content source\n   is the context window — do not re-read the transcript.\n\n   *Backfill mode:* The argument is either a session ID or a `.jsonl` path.\n   - If it looks like a path: use it directly; session ID is the filename stem.\n   - If it looks like an ID: `find ~/.claude/projects -name \"<id>.jsonl\" 2>/dev/null | head -1`\n     to locate the transcript.\n   - Run `python3 $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/tools/extract_session.py <jsonl-path> --cap 40000`\n     and read its output — this is your content source instead of the context window.\n   - There is no live `tokens:` line to write; the SessionEnd hook already wrote\n     one in the floor entry. Preserve it when updating the index entry in step 3.'), (219,27,'2026-06-18 14:47:14','6b9182e6-75bd-4fca-b800-285bb33d00d6','edit_path','docs/decisions/2026-06-18-two-tier-autoflagger.md',NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0','**How forks get both tiers.** By forking. The tier-1 rule lives in this repo\'s own\n`CLAUDE.md` and the tier-2 script in `tools/` — a fork inherits both unchanged by forking\n(§No profiles, §What CMS is). This is the right channel *for forks*: a fork keeps CMS\'s\nown `CLAUDE.md`, not the starter template.\n\n**Open (separate channel, not done).** `starter/CLAUDE.md.template` is the baseline\n`CLAUDE.md` a *template-scaffolded* project starts from — and it legitimately carries\nbaseline behavioral rules (Context hygiene, Execution discipline, etc.), not just identity\nplaceholders. So seeding the tier-1 judge rule there is a real option *if* we want\nprojects scaffolded from the template to get autoflagging by default — it is **not** the\nretired payload pattern (that retired the generator copying single-sourced *machinery*\ninto N projects; `CLAUDE.md` rules are per-project-owned by design). It simply doesn\'t\naffect forks. Deferred as an explicit choice, not a forbidden one.'), (220,3,'2026-06-18 14:50:07','60ace78a-2770-4c8d-90f1-cdc9daae9cf1','session_start',NULL,NULL,'761086243ef060708b87148537b73d83f4bc72ab',1,'claude-opus-4-8','0.1.0',NULL);
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS `takeaways`;
CREATE TABLE `takeaways` (
  `id` int NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `created` datetime NOT NULL,
  `kind` enum('gotcha','rule','preference') NOT NULL,
  `scope` varchar(255),
  `trigger_kind` enum('edit_path','session_start','on_demand') NOT NULL,
  `trigger_spec` varchar(255),
  `one_liner` varchar(500) NOT NULL,
  `full_content` text,
  `source` varchar(255),
  `status` enum('active','retired') NOT NULL DEFAULT '1',
  `mirror` enum('none','candidate','mirrored') NOT NULL DEFAULT '1',
  PRIMARY KEY (`id`)
) ENGINE=InnoDB AUTO_INCREMENT=29 DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_0900_bin;
INSERT INTO `takeaways` (`id`,`created`,`kind`,`scope`,`trigger_kind`,`trigger_spec`,`one_liner`,`full_content`,`source`,`status`,`mirror`) VALUES (1,'2026-06-11 15:45:14','gotcha','instantiation','edit_path','payload/*,payload/**,method/*','Prose here must not contain a literal {{ outside a real payload slot — reference placeholder syntax without the braces, or the linter/instantiation grep treats it as unfilled and blocks.','From the first portfolio-site instantiation: generated road.md prose mentioned \'{{\'-style placeholders, tripping the step-3 \'grep {{\' gate. Fix: reword (\'double-brace-style\'). The cms_lint placeholder check exempts code spans, but the instantiation gate greps raw.','portfolio-site run 2026-06-11','active','none'), (2,'2026-06-11 15:45:15','gotcha','harness','edit_path','tools/*','Permission deny rules match tokens anywhere in a compound Bash command — an \'rm -rf\' cleanup clause or a \'curl\' trips the deny even when the main verb is allowed. Split the command or use plain \'rm -r\'.','Hit during the dolt install: three denials. Two causes: curl* is deny-listed in brain2 settings (worked around with python urllib, with user authorization), and rm -rf in a trailing cleanup clause matched \'Bash(rm -rf *)\'. Deny rules are per-token over the whole command string.','CMS session 2026-06-11','active','none'), (3,'2026-06-11 15:45:15','preference','meta','session_start',NULL,'Ship the thing that fires (skill, hook, check, prompt, row) — not prose describing it. Material-shaped additions to this repo regress to the doc genre default; that failure built v1.','The CMS v1 post-mortem: three sessions produced 22 polished docs nobody loads. The user\'s standing want is operative machinery. When adding here, ask: what is the trigger, and what fires?','CMS v1 post-mortem 2026-06-11','active','none'), (4,'2026-06-11 17:18:09','gotcha','store','edit_path','tools/takeaway*.py','Adding or repurposing a status enum value? Every existing WHERE status = ... filter silently excludes it — grep all consumers before assuming bookkeeping statuses are inert (this is how mirrored rows stopped firing).','The method doc said mirrored takeaways stay active locally; the executors filtered status = \'active\' only, so the flip to mirrored became an unintended kill switch. Found by validating the monition contract against live behavior. Fix: status IN (\'active\',\'mirrored\'). General form: a new enum value defaults to excluded-everywhere — audit every filter on that column.','CMS/monition session 2026-06-11','active','candidate'), (5,'2026-06-11 17:18:09','gotcha','harness','edit_path','.claude/*','Hook commands with relative paths (python3 tools/x.py) break when the session shell cwd drifts — always use $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR in settings.json hook commands.','A PreToolUse hook failed mid-session with can-t-open-file because a prior Bash cd left the cwd in takeaways/. Hooks resolve relative paths against the live shell cwd, not the project root. Fix: python3 \"$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR\"/tools/x.py. Pipe-test after wiring.','CMS/monition session 2026-06-11','active','candidate'), (6,'2026-06-11 17:18:10','gotcha','store','edit_path','tools/takeaway*.py,.claude/*','Manually piping test JSON into the disclosure executors inserts real rows into firings — use a recognizable synthetic session_id and delete those rows after the test, or the eval data is polluted.','Pipe-testing the hook fix logged firings under session pipetest; cleaned with DELETE FROM firings WHERE session_id = pipetest. The firings table is training data — synthetic firings bias precision metrics.','CMS/monition session 2026-06-11','active','none'), (7,'2026-06-12 00:44:01','rule','handoffs, resumption','on_demand','handoff, resume, pick up','A handoff\'s State section is a snapshot, not ground truth — verify every \"not done yet\" claim against git log before executing; handoffs go stale within a day when other sessions touch the same work.','The cutover handoff (2026-06-11) claimed no CMS changes had landed; commit 1b8dda9 from a later session the same day had already done steps 2-3. Executing the handoff literally would have redone or clobbered finished work. Workaround: treat the handoff\'s Next-actions step-1 verification as mandatory and extend it — diff each State claim against git log since the handoff\'s date before acting on any of them.','2026-06-12 cutover-completion session','active','candidate'), (8,'2026-06-12 00:44:02','rule','contracts, interchange formats','edit_path','payload/*','Implementing one side of a format owned elsewhere? Self-written fixtures can\'t catch dialect drift — round-trip the same fixture through the owning implementation before shipping.','The tier-0 executor parsed all six fixture cases correctly, but only monition init --adopt on the identical file proved both serializations agree (3 imported, 1 rejected with the expected per-block reason). When a contract names a single format owner, its implementation is the test oracle; passing your own parser\'s tests only proves self-consistency.','2026-06-12 tier-0 payload build, commit 27a24bc','active','candidate'), (9,'2026-06-12 03:45:13','rule','cross-repo, ownership, method docs','edit_path','method/*','Creating or extending a method discipline another repo must mirror? Assign the canonical owner and the propagation channel in the same change — unowned cross-repo text degenerates into hand-carried refreshes within hours.','lesson-routing.md was built and queued for monition without deciding ownership; refinements then had to be hand-carried twice the same day until a confer settled it (CMS owns canonical, routing-version stamp, monition mirrors via monition sync\'s hash-check channel). The repo already had the template: the interchange format (monition owns, CMS cites). Ask at creation: who owns the canonical text, and how do changes reach the copies — if the answers aren\'t in the same commit, the friction is scheduled.','2026-06-12 routing/confer session, commits 00b64a8..a87e5b1','active','candidate'), (10,'2026-06-12 19:17:02','rule','consent-gate,crash-recovery','on_demand','crash,crashed,interrupted,resume,last session,take it from there','Resuming after a crash: uncommitted edits to governed files (method/, payload/) sit in a half-crossed consent gate — re-propose them before committing, even if the diff looks finished.','A crash leaves edits that were written but whose consent-gate acceptance was never confirmed — the diff alone won\'t tell you whether the user approved them. This session the in-flight package (tooling.md bullet, session_tokens hook, settings wiring) was re-proposed and re-accepted before commit, and re-checking surfaced two violations of an hours-old committed lesson (t5 anchoring) that would otherwise have shipped. Workaround: treat any uncommitted governed-file edit found at resume as un-consented until re-confirmed. Distinct from t7 (verify handoff STATE claims against git log) — that\'s stale state, this is unconfirmed consent.','session c06f513e / 2026-06-12','active','none'), (11,'2026-06-13 13:50:03','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand','claude -p, headless claude, nested claude, claude subprocess, strict-mcp-config, setting-sources','Shelling out to `claude -p` from inside a project? The child inherits the cwd\'s hooks + .mcp.json — it stalls on MCP health-checks, logs a firing into your eval substrate, and writes its own transcript. Isolate the call.','A nested `claude -p` run with cwd inside a project loads that project\'s settings (hooks) and .mcp.json. Three symptoms: (1) the first call hangs to rc=124 — an MCP server health-check spawn; (2) every call fires the project\'s prompt/session hooks, logging a firing into the firings/eval table and polluting the substrate; (3) each call writes its own session JSONL under ~/.claude/projects, which a corpus builder then re-summarises (the archive eats its own tail). Hermetic recipe: --strict-mcp-config (ignore project .mcp.json) + --setting-sources \'\' (load NO settings, so no hooks fire — auth still loads from credentials) + --no-session-persistence (no transcript stub). Do NOT use --bare: it also drops the apiKeyHelper, so the call fails \'Not logged in\'. And --json-schema hangs the call to timeout in this setup — enforce output shape with a prompt + retry-on-drift, not the schema flag.','session cee33bbd; commit a9ecec7','active','candidate'), (12,'2026-06-13 13:50:04','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand','summarise, summariser, LLM judge, extract, classify, structured output, output format drift','An LLM fed a transcript that\'s itself a handoff/advisory/Q&A will echo that voice and ignore your output format. Put the format spec in the system prompt, the content in the user turn, and retry on drift.','When you summarise/extract/judge over natural-language content, a transcript whose own register is conversational (advisory, handoff, Q&A) drags the model out of your required format — it \'answers\' in that voice instead of emitting your fields. Mitigations that worked: (1) put the format spec in the SYSTEM prompt and pass the content as the user turn — don\'t put instructions plus a tiny example together in one user message, the model mistakes the format template for an example and asks \'where\'s the input?\'; (2) detect drift cheaply (required leading token missing) and retry once with a stricter \'output ONLY the format, no preamble\' instruction — only the minority that drift pay for the second call. CLI --json-schema would force structure but hangs here, so prompt + retry is the fix.','session cee33bbd','active','candidate'), (13,'2026-06-13 13:50:05','rule',NULL,'on_demand','backfill, batch job, OOM, killed, resumable, idempotent, long run','A long sequential batch of nested LLM/`claude` spawns will get OOM-killed mid-run on a memory-tight box — make each step idempotent (skip-existing) and wrap the run in a re-launch loop so a kill resumes instead of restarting.','Spawning hundreds of nested claude processes sequentially on a memory-constrained box (e.g. WSL with several concurrent interactive sessions) reliably triggers an OOM kill partway through — and because it\'s SIGKILL there\'s no traceback, so distinguish it from a code bug (a crash leaves a traceback; a kill doesn\'t). Make the run survivable: (1) idempotent unit of work — skip if the output artifact already exists, so a re-run resumes cheaply; (2) wrap the run in a shell loop that re-invokes until it prints its completion line — the lightweight loop shell survives the kill and each attempt advances. After a kill, confirm no orphaned headless -p child processes leaked (ps).','session cee33bbd','active','candidate'), (14,'2026-06-13 18:54:16','preference','tooling, embeddings','on_demand','chromadb, sentence-transformers, embedding index, RAG, vector index, local-model venv, MiniLM','Building/verifying an embeddings tool (chromadb/sentence-transformers)? Don\'t pay a fresh ~2GB venv install — reuse an existing deps-having venv; the Chroma index and HF model cache are portable across venvs.','sentence-transformers pulls torch (~2GB) plus a model download, so a fresh per-project venv on a memory/disk-tight box is slow and wasteful. Any interpreter that already has chromadb + sentence-transformers (e.g. another local-RAG project\'s venv) can build and query the index — the on-disk Chroma DB and the ~/.cache/huggingface model cache are shared and portable across venvs. Use one to verify correctness immediately; defer the dedicated venv install + MCP registration to a documented one-time step.','session c0f253d5 / commit 7e635db','active','candidate'), (15,'2026-06-13 23:23:51','gotcha','self-audit, incubator, discipline-coverage','on_demand','missing discipline, discipline gap, self-audit, coverage gap, what disciplines, audit method','Auditing the incubator\'s own discipline coverage from inside CMS? Its doc-shaped project-type hides gaps that only bite the code-heavy projects it generates — audit against a differently-shaped downstream project, not CMS itself.','The tech-debt-capture gap survived because CMS is doc-shaped and barely accrues code-debt, so the missing discipline was invisible from inside — it took a code-heavy downstream (VVsim) to surface it. A producer is a biased sample of what it produces: cross-check disciplines against a generated project whose shape actually exercises them.','confer tech-debt shelf / 78e9cc9','active','none'), (16,'2026-06-14 01:37:56','gotcha','git, dates, boundary','on_demand','git --since, --until, commits since, approxidate, git log date','Computing a git log --since/--until boundary? A bare date (--since 2026-06-14) fills its time-of-day from the current wall clock (git approxidate), so same-day commits silently drift in/out — pass an explicit datetime (<date> 00:00:00).','Approxidate fills missing fields from \'now\', so --since <bare-date> means \'<date> at the current time\', not midnight. Fix: pass an explicit \'<date> 00:00:00\'. Testing note: this class of boundary bug passes unit tests written with arbitrary dates and only bites at the real same-day/now boundary — exercise it there (dogfooding a feature on today\'s own session does this for free).','session 7012d564, commit 0fe4895','active','candidate'), (17,'2026-06-14 01:38:18','rule','method-docs, incubator, doc-vs-machinery','on_demand','doc-lag, genuine gap, remaining method docs, missing method doc','Calling a missing method-doc a \'genuine gap\'? Grep payload/ for its firing artifacts first — the machinery often already ships and only the discipline doc lags (doc-lag, not work-lag).','This session, write-path.md was called a \'no-proxy genuine gap\' on a surface read; investigating found the consent gate, decisions shelf, and craft hook all already shipping in payload — plain doc-lag, not work-lag. Before classifying a doc\'s absence as a missing capability, grep for the firing artifacts it would govern.','session 7012d564','active','candidate'), (18,'2026-06-14 15:28:02','gotcha','verification, stale-state, ground-truth','on_demand','deferred, already built, already exists, is it shipped, the doc says, road.md, stale, outdated, current state','Long or multi-day session, or sibling repos / parallel sessions in play? A doc or your earlier-in-session belief is probably stale — before asserting what exists or what a tool does, check ground truth (--help, grep, git log).','Bit 3x this session: claimed CMS had \'no tech-debt system\' when it had been built in parallel; repeated road.md\'s \'score deferred\' when the CLI already shipped score/tune; called write-path.md a \'no-proxy genuine gap\' on a surface read. Each was a stale doc or stale earlier-session model beating current reality. The fix is one cheap check against ground truth — --help / grep / git log. Distinct from t17 (method-doc-gap-specific) and t7 (handoff-specific): the general case across any doc, tool, or sibling repo.','session 7012d564','active','none'), (19,'2026-06-14 16:44:20','rule','method-docs, incubator, doc-vs-machinery, work-lag','on_demand','work-lag, does it actually work, is it wired, is it built, method-doc mechanism, described mode, firing artifact, drains, sweep','About to tell the user a method-doc\'s mechanism/mode works? Grep the owning skill/payload for its firing artifact first — docs describe modes that were never wired (work-lag, the mirror of doc-lag).','This session dispatch.md described an autonomous-triage \'sweep\' and I told the user \'/dispatch drains the shelf in triage mode\' — but the dispatch skill ships only generate+execute; no triage mode exists. A method doc describing a capability is not proof the firing artifact exists. Before relying on or explaining a documented mechanism, grep the owning skill/prompt/hook for the thing that actually fires it. Mirror of takeaway 17 (doc-lag): there the doc lagged shipped machinery; here machinery lags the doc. Either way: verify doc<->machinery by grepping the artifact.','session fbe732fc / commit 32a69c0','active','none'), (20,'2026-06-14 23:03:35','preference','planning, deferral, user-preference','on_demand','defer, deferred, do later, park, parked, leave till later, gated on eval, needs eval data','About to park something as defer / do-later? Check whether the stated rationale (needs eval data / usage volume / too speculative) actually applies to THIS item or was inherited from a sibling it got bundled with — if it is cheap + deterministic and the reason is borrowed, lean toward building now.','On the 2026-06-13 session-archive staleness annotation, the spec had deferred it into the same gated-on-eval-data / usage-volume bucket as the grep-vs-semantic retrieval router — but staleness is a deterministic git count, not a tuned ranking, so the eval-gating rationale fit the router, not staleness; it had been bundled in by association. How to apply: before accepting a defer, check whether the stated rationale actually applies to THIS item or was inherited from a sibling it got bundled with. If it is cheap + deterministic and the rationale is borrowed, surface that and lean toward building now. Still keep genuinely evidence-gated work deferred — separate that from incidentally-bundled work, not stop deferring. Related: lesson-routing.md (under thin evidence prefer the reversible row) holds for genuinely uncertain items.','migrated from auto-memory (defer-cost-preference)','active','none'), (21,'2026-06-17 16:43:22','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand','new module, naming, backends, seam','Before creating a module named after a common seam pattern (backends.py, store.py, hooks.py), grep the repo — that name may already own a different seam.','Monition has backends.py (replay agent seam); a new storage_backends.py had to be named differently to avoid collision. The grep takes 2 seconds; the silent name collision costs a debugging session. Common seam names: backends, store, hooks, adapters, runners.','session 2026-06-17 monition storage-backend refactor','active','none'), (22,'2026-06-17 16:43:23','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand','sqlite, pragma, schema validation, table_info','SQLite PRAGMA table_info(t) returns [] for a missing table — no exception — schema validation loops need an explicit empty-list guard, not exception catching.','Unlike MySQL DESCRIBE (which raises on missing tables), PRAGMA table_info is silent when the table doesn\'t exist. Schema-validation loops that caught subprocess errors to detect missing tables must switch to checking for empty list return. Source: porting the dolt DESCRIBE-based fingerprint check to SQLite in monition.','session 2026-06-17 monition storage-backend refactor','active','none'), (23,'2026-06-17 16:43:25','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand','sqlite, now(), datetime, mysql, backend, dialect','SQLite uses datetime(\'now\') where MySQL/Dolt uses NOW() — translate at the backend boundary, not at every call site.','Existing SQL strings written for Dolt use NOW(). Adding _adapt(sql) to SqliteBackend with a simple replace keeps all dialect bridging inside the backend class; call sites stay unchanged. If you try to fix it at the call sites, you scatter dialect awareness everywhere.','session 2026-06-17 monition storage-backend refactor','active','none'), (24,'2026-06-18 02:56:38','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand',NULL,'Making a repo public publishes its ENTIRE git history — scrubbing the working tree leaves provenance/secrets/firings in past commits. Publish a clean-slate squash (orphan branch, single commit); run the final pre-publish leak scan UNFILTERED — do not exclude dirs you skipped while scrubbing.','Why: a public repo exposes git log; old commits keep everything scrubbed from the working tree (CMS: 41 commits had brain2 refs; dump.sql firings recoverable). Tracked handoffs/ with brain2 refs slipped through because the scrub sweeps excluded handoffs/ — the pre-publish leak scan must NOT carry that exclusion. Workaround: git checkout --orphan <release>; one commit; verify git rev-list --count ==1 and git grep on the orphan; keep full history in a private archive repo.','2026-06-18 forkable-refactor publish','active','none'), (25,'2026-06-18 02:56:40','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand',NULL,'gh repo create <name> silently no-ops if the repo already exists — the --public/visibility flag is NOT applied, and a pre-existing default branch can carry old history. After any repo create-or-push, verify visibility + branches + default via gh repo view before trusting it.','On publish: bobrobaker/CMS pre-existed PRIVATE with a stale brain2-laden master as default; gh repo create said \"Name already exists\" and --public was ignored (nothing leaked, by luck). Caught only by gh repo view --json visibility,defaultBranchRef + gh api repos/OWNER/REPO/branches. Fix: set default to the clean branch, delete the stale branch (back up first), then flip visibility via gh api -X PATCH repos/OWNER/REPO -F private=false (gh repo edit --visibility was unrecognized in this gh version).','2026-06-18 forkable-refactor publish','active','none'), (26,'2026-06-18 02:56:41','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand',NULL,'Installing a Python CLI in a bootstrap/install script: never pip install into system Python (PEP 668 refuses on modern Debian/Ubuntu/WSL) — use uv tool / pipx if present, else a dedicated venv + a launcher symlinked onto PATH. Detect the tool with command -v <cli>, not a python import-check (which false-positives from any cwd containing a same-named subdir).','Both bit the CMS bootstrap: (1) pip install -e into system python failed with externally-managed-environment; (2) the guard python3 -c import-monition false-positived because CMS has a monition/ subdir (namespace package, __file__ None) and checked the wrong interpreter (the CLI lives in its own venv). 2026 practice: uv tool install / pipx isolate CLI tools and sidestep PEP 668; fallback with neither is python3 -m venv + ln -s the launcher into ~/.local/bin.','2026-06-18 forkable-refactor publish','active','none'), (27,'2026-06-18 14:15:17','rule','decisions,governance,immutability','edit_path','docs/decisions/*.md','Editing a decision doc? They are immutable point-in-time records — don\'t rewrite a landed call. To change it, add a NEW dated decision and annotate the old one as superseded (doc/section/sentence, whatever fits). The only allowed edit to an existing decision is that supersession pointer.','Decision docs in docs/decisions/ record what was decided and why, when. Rewriting one erases the reasoning a later session needs. Convention (docs/decisions/README.md): supersede, don\'t rewrite — write a new dated YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md stating the new call and why it replaces the old, then annotate the OLD entry with a \'Superseded by\' pointer at the granularity that changed (doc-level banner for a full overturn, inline paragraph/sentence note for a partial one), leaving its original body intact. Exception: while authoring a brand-new entry in the same change, normal drafting edits are fine — this guards landed decisions, not the one being written.','2026-06-18 two-tier-autoflagger session','active','none'), (28,'2026-06-18 14:50:18','gotcha',NULL,'on_demand','search_sessions OR \"can\'t find session\" OR semantic session search','floor-only sessions are grep-visible but semantically invisible — search_sessions only indexes sessions/*.md; a session without /wrap-session has no summary file and won\'t appear in semantic search','The semantic search tool only embeds ~/.claude/logs/sessions/*.md (summary files written by /wrap-session). The SessionEnd hook writes a floor entry to sessions.md but never creates a summary file. Fix: /wrap-session <id> (backfill mode) creates the summary; re-run index.py to embed it. Keyword grep on sessions.md always works.','session/6d82d5ae','active','none');
